div.p:
He was exactly juſt to all men in his Dealings and Trade; of this there is no queſtion: And thoſe that knew him well can tell that in making up his Accounts he was ſcrupulouſly ſo, and took great care that an errour or miſtake in his Correſpondent ſhould not be to his prejudice. He was greatly careful to do no wrong, and had learnt to forgive. I doubt not but the Character given to Pomponius Atticus belongs to him: Nullas inimicitias geſſit;
               C. Nepos. P. Attic. 
               quod neque laedebat quenquam; neque ſiquam injuriam acceperat, non malebat ulciſci, quam obliviſci. He had no quarrels, for he did no injury; and if any were done to him, he rather choſe to forget than to revenge. There are few men, perhaps, have paſſed through the World with leſs offence to it than this good man hath done. His ways pleaſed God, and He ſo provided, that his Enemies (if he had any ſuch) ſhould be at peace with him.
